INSERT INTO event VALUES(3255,'545','2015-03-31T12:53:19Z',454,13,'HGustavs','comment','We are given a system that is considered complete. No old things are allowed to change unless non-working. New featurescolumnsdocumentation can be added  but any working existing code should largely remain unchanged. Apart from the philosophical issues  this is particularly important since any such changes may result in consequences for the other sub-projects or may cause unforeseen problems in other parts of the code. It is a general rule  that working code should not be broken.','UNK');
INSERT INTO event VALUES(3257,'545','2015-03-31T13:27:15Z',454,14,'HGustavs','comment','Off the table. The database is as is. Many of the identifiers are numbers so that data does not leak. If data escapes the system  neither the login name nor password is compromised even if data with the user id leaks. Knowing user id does not help an attacker to guess passwords or login informaiton.','UNK');
INSERT INTO event VALUES(3258,'545','2015-03-31T13:30:45Z',454,14,'HGustavs','comment','We can add tables or add columns but change of existing things is off the table unless the change is local i.e. only affects a limited amount of code... especially if that code is broken. This case is at odds with this rule as it is a very basic function  deep in the system.','UNK');
INSERT INTO event VALUES(3259,'545','2015-03-31T13:36:20Z',454,14,'HGustavs','comment','I however do agree that unique identifiers that are random militates even better against guessing  so a better solution would be a completely random identifier... now an attacker can start with 1 and begin to guess.... which is worse than guessing a completely random sequence of numbers. But... as I said  we only change things with minimal side effects and only if broken  so we leave this particular general issue as is.','UNK');
