INSERT INTO event VALUES(4430,'708','2015-04-07T18:52:47Z',461,19,'HGustavs','comment','The problem is the following A width-adaptive design with only css if page is narrow we do not want the icons one below another. It should adapt and reduce until the menu items no longer fit  at which point scroll bars should appear. Simple html layout readable directly in the file  without changes When page is resized  no javascript should be needed to compensate If the csscode could be reduced without bad effect  errors with reduced size or failure to adapt to web page width  I do not personally mind. But if it does not reduce the htmlor css or breaks the page there is no point to this change.','UNK');
INSERT INTO event VALUES(4432,'708','2015-04-08T08:22:46Z',462,9,'HGustavs','comment','The problem is that it is quite complex to make a width-adaptable layout using pure css. We want a menu on the right  and a layout that adapts when the page is resized. This tends to often result in very complex layouts with deeply nested divs and spans and lots of css to account for the adaptation to the screen width  whereas a table layout just works.... Float-left and float-right are difficult to get right such layouts often use absolute sizes in pixels to work properly. If the screen layout changes or the size of a text field or image changes  these absolutes need to be updated in the css or updated live using javascript. One common failure of floating layouts is that in HTML elements want to stack vertically  not horizontally  if you want 5 buttons with unknown width  then to the right  a button of unknown width and between them space to fill out the rest.... this may or may not be easy to do. And it may result in the page breaking  at a certain width of screen or size of button... the buttonst will start to stack vertically rather than horizontally.... whereas when using a table this is automatic  nearly no css and only basic html in the static file.','UNK');
INSERT INTO event VALUES(4433,'708','2015-04-08T08:25:07Z',462,9,'HGustavs','comment','If you feel up to the task I am not against it  but to me  it is better to focus on some issue that is broken or missing rather than spending time on repairing something that is not exactly broken. Having said that  if you can produce a demotest page that works and it is better than the existing one I dont mind having a standardized html layout.','UNK');
