INSERT INTO event VALUES(15785,'2136','2016-04-14T10:22:54Z',834,11,'HGustavs','comment','No this does not quite do what we need. Do we have any performance data to support that the javascript is the reason that the view is slow? I am thinking that it is a database issue.... since the processor in the browsing computer should be able to process millions of data items relatively fast. If javascript is the problem this can be solved by not updating the view on every change  but on refresh. We need two things... to get an overview of all students  who has submitted at all  and who has not submitted anything  kind of a where are we view. to get an overview of specific students for specific assignments to do marking. I am thinking that we can do both  with filters. There should be a line limiter e.g. the sql should be: select * from blabla limit 25 i.e. we only collect information for 25 students at a time unless we explicitly say: get all students... so I suggest a dropdown students with options for 0-25  25-49  50-75  etc etc and ALL as the last option  with 0-25 being the default. This way we see only 25 students at a time except for when we are viewing all students for making result lists on paper or to get an overview of all students. If we combine this with a filter for each assignment that we can click..... to limit the queries to for instance only showing dugga1 ... or dugga1 and dugga2 ... By doing this we are limiting the database to a small subset without missing any information. I however DO like the way that we are sorting the stuff with the moments first and each dugga afterwards.... much better than the current layout.','UNK');
INSERT INTO event VALUES(15786,'2136','2016-04-14T10:30:04Z',834,11,'HGustavs','comment','Also from a usability standpoint I want to limit the number of clicks as much as possible.... If I have to do one additional click for each student this makes thousands of clicks and scrolls for each marking of an assignment  which is unsuitable from a work-flow-standpoint. We want a workflow that is: click-mark-click-mark-click-mark without additional clicks or scroll actions. But with the solution I suggested I get very few clicks. One click to limit marking to only assignment 1 or for example two clicks for assignment 1 and assignment 2.  checkbox or modal button for each assignment  Then I can immediately mark the first 25 entries for assignment 1.... then I can move on to the next 25 with one click. The load on the database access requirements should be much smaller if we only do 25 students times a few columns at a time  ideally one at a time .','UNK');
INSERT INTO event VALUES(15787,'2136','2016-04-14T10:38:55Z',834,11,'HGustavs','comment','In short  I vote for Make the layout in the mockup with separate moments and assignments  which is much clearer than the current Moment A Assignment 1 Assignment 2 Momment B Assignment 3 Add filtering  to filter out only the assignment s  that we are marking at the moment. Limit view to 25 students at a time but with an option to all students with confirmation  are you sure?  alert to get a full course overview of all students. @a97marbr suggested that if possible we add an option for sorting the student list on oldest unmarked assignment or newest unmarked assignment in addition to the current name-based sorting.','UNK');
INSERT INTO event VALUES(15789,'2136','2016-04-14T17:34:50Z',834,18,'HGustavs','comment','Can you take me through the arrows and what they mean. Is the arrows the sorting order? I am thinking along these lines - Show 25-50  assignment 1-3 and moment A are shown  we sort on newest unmarked in assignment 3. The rest of the moments and assignments are hidden. Any combination of assignments or moments could be chosen. Perhaps it would be a good idead to have a button somewhere to show all assignments. Somehow the marking icon is lost in your mockup  so I added it back. The yellow background indicates that it is an un-marked assignment. If we sort on this column we sort the whole table on the hand-in dates of unmarked assignments for the third assignment.','UNK');
INSERT INTO event VALUES(15790,'2136','2016-04-15T08:22:54Z',835,9,'HGustavs','comment','Thinking about this overnight.... I came up with this suggestion. Not all information is required to be read every refresh  only the results change rapidly  but student enrollment and moments change more rarely. So I suggest reading the information twice. A service call READSTATIC which is called once per page refresh to collect the student list and the moment list  anything else is static? the dugga-content?  and then store this information in in-memory javascript arrays. A service call that is used to read the results and render the list e.g. READRESULTS. For rendering the table we read from memory  rather than from the JSON data most of the time for the student list  moment list and so on. This can reduce the database load even further  this way when a mark is set  or when we read the assignment or results of a student we only read that information and refresh the list  we do not read the full database. Also the application will be sligtly more separeted on the service level.','UNK');
