INSERT INTO event VALUES(36048,'4341','2018-04-06T09:13:48Z',1556,10,'HGustavs','comment','Or an even simpler more general way. One that just creates the table And the columns are added one by one separately. This way  adding columns or adding tables use the same code for each column. So there would instead be a structure that looks something like this  not syntax checked but roughly like this : [ ÔÇÿVersionÔÇÖ:ÔÇÿv0.10ÔÇÖ  [ ÔÇÿcreateÔÇÖ  ÔÇÿusersÔÇÖ  column users ÔÇÿuidÔÇÖ  ÔÇÿintÔÇÖ  ÔÇÿUNSIGNED NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENTÔÇÖ  column users ÔÇÿnameÔÇÖ  ÔÇÿvarchar 30 ÔÇÖ  ÔÇÿNULLÔÇÖ  column users ÔÇÿemailÔÇÖ  ÔÇÿvarchar 30 ÔÇÖ  ÔÇÿNOT NULLÔÇÖ ]   ÔÇÿVersionÔÇÖ:ÔÇÿv0.11ÔÇÖ  [ ÔÇÿcreateÔÇÖ  ÔÇÿstudentÔÇÖ  column  studentÔÇÿuidÔÇÖ  ÔÇÿintÔÇÖ  ÔÇÿUNSIGNED NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENTÔÇÖ  column users class  ÔÇÿvarchar 30 ÔÇÖ  ÔÇÿNOT NULLÔÇÖ ]   ÔÇÿVersionÔÇÖ:ÔÇÿv0.12ÔÇÖ  [ column gregerÔÇÿuidÔÇÖ  ÔÇÿintÔÇÖ  ÔÇÿUNSIGNED NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENTÔÇÖ  ] ] This way there is no additional code needed for adding one more column to users in v0.11 The SQL would then be  roughly.. have not syntax checked at ALL : CREATE TABLE users; ALTER TABLE USERS ADD COLUMN uid INTEGER UNSIGNED NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT; ...','UNK');
