INSERT INTO event VALUES(88716,'8387','2020-04-22T11:01:54Z',2303,12,'HGustavs','comment','That diagram is wrong so it is difficult to say what should happen. An identifying relationship is mandatory on at least the side connecting to the weak entity. It can be on both though. In that diagram the relationships are not identifying so it can be either way. What happens if we draw an identifying relationship What happens if we change a relationship from identifying to non-identifying? What happend if we change the cardinalitites? imho only identifying relationship with inverted or wrong cardinalities should be forbidden  if that  even. I prefer a system that allows everything since the diagram may be incomplete as a partial step between two valid states. e.g if we have two entities that are not weakly related  the process should not be constrained if we first make the relationship weak then the entity or vice versa. Or if we first make the entity weak then change the relationship. OR if the relationship is N:N which is close to the semantics of a weak relationship we need to changge from N:N normal to 1:N weak. There are 6 permutations for how we can go from one valid diagram to another. It is only at the last step that we have a valid diagram. And all 6 permutations end up at the same destination. It is impossible for the computer to anticipate this  and diferentiate between a partial step towards a valid state and an end state that is faulty by mistake.','UNK');
INSERT INTO event VALUES(88717,'8387','2020-04-22T11:15:00Z',2303,12,'HGustavs','comment','And by the way there is a nearly endless set of permutations even if we only go so far as three entities and two relationships. The factorial of 12 is 479.001.600 Imagine a diagram with 1000 entities... https:en.wikipedia.orgwikiFactorial','UNK');
